        <body>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <head type="title"><title type="poem" corresp="#JRTHESUN">&#x201C;The Sun&#x201D;</title></head>
                
                <div type="section" xml:id="TITLE">
                    <head type="section">Title</head>
                    <p>In the presentation copy, now bound in <title type="manuscript" corresp="#MSXI">MS XI</title>, <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName> wrote the title as 
                        <title type="poem" corresp="#JRTHESUN">&#x201C;<hi rend="doubleletter-fill">THE SUN</hi>&#x201D;</title>; 
                        and in <title type="manuscript" corresp="#MSIII">MS III</title>, he wrote the title in capitals without emphasis, 
                        as <title type="poem" corresp="#JRTHESUN">&#x201C;THE SUN&#x201D;</title>.</p>
                    <p>See <ref type="note" subtype="bibliographical" target="title_citation_note.php">System of Title Citation for Works</ref>.</p>
                </div>
                
                <div type="section" xml:id="GENRE">
                    <head type="section">Genre</head>
                    <p><ref type="note" subtype="bibliographical" target="new_years_poems_note.php">New Year&#x02019;s poem.</ref></p>
                </div>
                
                <div type="section" xml:id="MAJORMS">
                    <head type="section">Manuscripts</head>
                    <p><!-- TAG, ADD APPARATUS REFS --><ref type="apparatus" subtype="manuscript" target="msxi_apparatus.php"><title type="manuscript" corresp="#MSXI">MS XI</title></ref>; <ref type="apparatus" subtype="manuscript" target="msiii_apparatus.php#"><title type="manuscript" corresp="#MSIII">MS III</title></ref>.</p>
                    <p>In <title type="manuscript" corresp="#MSXI">MS XI</title>, <title type="poem" corresp="#JRTHESUN">&#x201C;The Sun&#x201D;</title> is printed by <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName> in pencil as a presentation copy for <date when="1828-01-01">New Year&#x02BC;s 1828</date>, followed on the same sheet by 
                        <ref type="apparatus" target="glenfarg_apparatus.php"><title type="poem" corresp="#JRGLENFARG">&#x201C;Glenfarg&#x201D; <hi rend="italic">and</hi> &#x201C;Glen of Glenfarg&#x201D; (&#x201C;Papa how pretty those icicles are&#x201D;)</title></ref>.</p>
                    <p>In <title type="manuscript" corresp="#MSIII">MS III</title>, which is a <ref type="note" subtype="bibliographical" target="red_book_note.php">Red Book</ref> devoted initially to <ref type="apparatus" target="harry_and_lucy_apparatus.php"><title type="lesson" corresp="#JRHARRYANDLUCYVOL2">&#x0201C;Harry and Lucy . . . Vol 2</title></ref>, 
                        <title type="poem" corresp="#JRTHESUN">&#x0201C;The Sun&#x0201D;</title> appears as the third poem in the <ref type="apparatus" target="msiii_poetry_anthology_2_apparatus.php"><title type="anthology" corresp="#MSIIIPOETRYANTHOLOGY2">MS III Second Poetry Anthology</title></ref>. 
                        Here, following the conclusion of the poem, <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName> prominently inscribed the date <date when="1828-01-01">&#x201C;January 1 1828&#x201D;</date>; and the poem is followed by a copy of 
                        <ref type="apparatus" target="glenfarg_apparatus.php"><title type="poem" corresp="#JRGLENFARG">&#x201C;Glenfarg&#x201D; <hi rend="italic">and</hi> &#x201C;Glen of Glenfarg&#x201D; (&#x201C;Papa how pretty those icicles are&#x201D;)</title></ref>, 
                        thus repeating the sequence of those two poems as printed in the presentation copy (<title type="manuscript" corresp="#MSXI">MS XI</title>).</p>
                    <p>Facsimiles by permission of <title type="archive" corresp="#BEINECKERUSKINCOLLECTION">John Ruskin Collection</title>, General Collection, <orgName corresp="#BEINECKE">Beinecke Rare Book and Manuscript Library</orgName>, <orgName corresp="#YALE">Yale University</orgName>. Transcriptions of texts and commentary &#x00A9; <persName corresp="#DCH">David C. Hanson</persName>.</p>
                    
                </div>
                <div type="section" xml:id="DATE">
                    <head type="section">Date</head>
                    <p><date when="1828-01-01">1 January 1828</date>.</p>
                    <p>Dated by <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName> both in the presentation copy (<ref type="apparatus" target="msxi_apparatus.php"><title type="manuscript" corresp="#MSXI">MS XI</title></ref>) and in the <ref type="note" subtype="bibliographical" target="red_book_note.php"><title type="manuscript" corresp="#JRREDBOOK">Red Book</title></ref> (<ref type="apparatus" subtype="manuscript" target="msiii_apparatus.php"><title type="manuscript" corresp="#MSIII">MS III</title></ref>).</p>
                    <p>See <ref type="note" subtype="bibliographical" target="date_citation_note.php">System of Date Citation</ref>.</p>
                </div>
                
                <div type="section" xml:id="COMPPUB">
                    <head type="section">Composition &#x0026; Publication</head>
                    <p>Published with omissions in <ref type="bibliography" target="bibliography.php#POEMS4D1891"><title type="book" corresp="#POEMS4D1891"><hi rend="italic">Poems</hi> (4<hi rend="superscript">o</hi>, <date when="1891">1891</date>)</title></ref>, 1:5&#x02013;6; and 
                        <ref type="bibliography" target="bibliography.php#POEMS8D1891"><title type="book" corresp="#POEMS8D1891"><hi rend="italic">Poems</hi> (8<hi rend="superscript">o</hi>, <date when="1891">1891</date>)</title></ref>, 1:5&#x02013;6; and in full in 
                        <ref type="bibliography" target="bibliography.php#JRWORKSLE"><persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName>, <title type="book" corresp="JRWORKSLE"><hi rend="italic">Works</hi></title></ref>, 2:260&#x02013;61.</p>
                    <p>As part of the <ref type="apparatus" target="msiii_poetry_anthology_2_apparatus.php"><title type="anthology" corresp="#MSIIIPOETRYANTHOLOGY2">MS III Second Poetry Anthology</title></ref> in <title type="manuscript" corresp="#MSIII">MS III</title>, 
                        <title type="poem" corresp="#JRTHESUN">&#x201C;The Sun&#x201D;</title> forms part of a cluster of <ref type="note" subtype="bibliographical" target="new_years_poems_note.php">New Year&#x02BC;s poems</ref>, 
                        including the poem paired with it in the holiday presentation for <date when="1828-01-01">New Year&#x02BC;s 1828</date>, 
                        <ref type="apparatus" target="glenfarg_apparatus.php"><title type="poem" corresp="#JRGLENFARG">&#x201C;Glenfarg&#x201D; <hi rend="italic">and</hi> &#x201C;Glen of Glenfarg&#x201D; (&#x201C;Papa how pretty those icicles are&#x201D;)</title></ref>, 
                        and the poem for <date when="1827-01-01">New Year&#x02BC;s 1827</date>, 
                        <ref type="apparatus" subtype="work" target="time_blank_verse_apparatus.php"><title type="poem" corresp="#JRTIMEBLANKVERSE">&#x201C;Time: Blank Verse&#x201D;</title></ref>. As an overlapping cluster, the anthology begins with a poem related to <title type="poem" corresp="#JRTHESUN">&#x201C;The Sun&#x201D;</title> thematically, as a poem about astronomy, 
                        <ref type="apparatus" target="constellations_apparatus.php"><title type="poem" corresp="#JRTHECONSTELLATIONS">&#x201C;The Constellations&#x201D;</title></ref> (see <ref type="internal" target="#DISCUSSION">Discussion</ref>).</p>
                </div>
                
                <div type="section" xml:id="DISCUSSION">
                    <head type="section">Discussion</head>
                    <div type="subsection" xml:id="SOURCES">
                        <head type="section">Sources</head>
                        <p>In the first half of <title type="poem" corresp="#JRTHESUN">&#x201C;THE SUN&#x201D;</title>, before swerving to its occasion as a holiday greeting, 
                            the poem is a hymn of praise. Specifically, with its image of &#x201C;mamma beside me&#x201D; walking in the garden, 
                            <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName>&#x02BC;s praise of the sun condenses 
                            <persName type="fictional" corresp="#ADAMJM">Adam</persName> and <persName type="fictional" corresp="#EVEJM">Eve</persName>&#x02BC;s morning hymn in book 5 of 
                            <title type="poem" corresp="#MILTONPARADISE"><hi rend="italic">Paradise Lost</hi></title>, &#x201C;These are thy glorious works, Parent of good&#x201D;. 
                            <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName> relies on <persName corresp="#JMILTON">Milton</persName>&#x02BC;s organizing trope of the sun&#x02BC;s course from dawn to noon to sunset, 
                            and he draws on some of <persName corresp="#JMILTON">Milton</persName>&#x02BC;s diction, such as invoking the sun to &#x201C;disperse&#x201D; the night:</p>
                            
            <floatingText>
                <body>
                    <div type="poem">
                        <lg type="blank_verse">
                        <l>Thou Sun, of this great World both Eye and Soul,</l>
                        <l>Acknowledge him thy Greater, sound his praise</l>
                        <l>In thy eternal course, both when thou climb&#x02BC;st,</l>
                        <l>And when high Noon hast gain&#x02BC;d, and when thou fall&#x02BC;st.</l>
                        <l>Moon, that now meet&#x02BC;st the orient Sun, now fli&#x02BC;st</l>
                        <l>With the fixt Stars, fixt in thir Orb that flies,</l>
                        <l>And yee five other wand&#x02BC;ring Fires that move</l>
                        <l>In mystic Dance not without Song, resound</l>
                        <l>His praise, who out of Darkness call&#x02BC;d up Light.</l>
                        <l>Air, and ye Elements the eldest birth</l>
                        <l>Of Nature&#x02BC;s Womb, that in quaternion run</l>
                        <l>Perpetual Circle, multiform, and mix</l>
                        <l>And nourish all things, let your ceaseless change</l>
                        <l>Vary to our great Maker still new praise.</l>
                        <l>Ye Mists and Exhalations that now rise</l>
                        <l>From Hill or steaming Lake, dusky or gray,</l>
                        <l>Till the Sun paint your fleecy skirts with Gold,</l>
                        <l>In honor to the World&#x02BC;s great Author rise,</l>
                        <l>Whether to deck with Clouds th&#x02BC; uncolor&#x02BC;d sky,</l>
                        <l>Or wet the thirsty Earth with falling showers,</l>
                        <l>Rising or falling still advance his praise.</l>
                        <l>His praise ye Winds, that from four Quarters blow,</l>
                        <l>Breathe soft or loud; and wave your tops, ye Pines,</l>
                        <l>With every Plant, in sign of Worship wave.</l>
                        <l>Fountains and yee, that warble, as ye flow,</l>
                        <l>Melodious murmurs, warbling tune his praise.</l>
                        <l>Join voices all ye living Souls;  ye Birds,</l>
                        <l>That singing up to Heaven Gate ascend,</l>
                        <l>Bear on your wings and in your notes his praise;</l>
                        <l>Yee that in Waters glide, and yee that walk</l>
                        <l>The Earth, and stately tread, or lowly creep;</l>
                        <l>Witness if I be silent, Morn or Even,</l>
                        <l>To Hill, or Valley, Fountain, or fresh shade</l>
                        <l>Made vocal by my Song, and taught his praise.</l>
                        <l>Hail universal Lord, be bounteous still</l>
                        <l>To give us only good; and if the night</l>
                        <l>Have gather&#x02BC;d aught of evil or conceal&#x02BC;d,</l>
                        <l>Disperse it, as now light dispels the dark.</l>
                        </lg>
                    </div>
                    <div>
                        <p>(<ref type="bibliography" target="bibliography.php#MILTONPOEMSPROSEHUGHES"><persName corresp="#JMILTON">Milton</persName>, <title type="poem" corresp="#MILTONPARADISE"><hi rend="italic">Paradise Lost</hi></title>, bk. 5, lines 171&#x2013;208, in <title type="book" corresp="#MILTONPOEMSPROSEHUGHES"><hi rend="italic">Complete Poems and Major Prose</hi></title>, ed. <persName corresp="#MYH">Hughes</persName></ref>, 306&#x2013;7)</p>
                    </div>
                </body>            
            </floatingText>
                    
                    <p>In <ref type="apparatus" subtype="manuscript" target="msiii_apparatus.php"><title type="manuscript" corresp="#MSIII">MS III</title></ref>, the astronomical theme forming the conclusion of 
                        <title type="poem" corresp="#JRTHESUN">&#x0201C;The Sun&#x0201D;</title> shares an interest in constellations with other works in <title type="manuscript" corresp="#MSIII">MS III</title>&#x02014;part of the narrative in 
                        <title type="lesson" corresp="#JRHARRYANDLUCYVOL2">&#x0201C;Harry and Lucy . . . Vol 2&#x0201D;</title>, and the poems 
                        <ref type="apparatus" target="constellations_apparatus.php"><title type="poem" corresp="#JRTHECONSTELLATIONS">&#x0201C;The Constellations: Northern, Some of the Zodiac, and Some of the Southern&#x0201D;</title></ref> and 
                        <ref type="apparatus" subtype="work" target="glen_of_glenfarg_apparatus"><title type="poem" corresp="#JRGLENOFGLENFARG">&#x201C;Glen of Glenfarg&#x201D; (&#x201C;Glen of Glenfarg thy beauteous rill&#x201D;)</title></ref>.</p>
                    
                </div>
               </div> 
            </div>
        </body>
